{
  "id": "019d32ba-8c9e-7f50-856f-1beb8e4775ec",
  "content": "# Decision: Build Native Structural Intelligence in adapter-git (Not Integrate GitNexus)\n\n## Context\n\nTeams onboarding corvia with established repos hit a cold-start problem. `corvia workspace ingest` produces text chunks but no structural relationships (call graphs, imports, module dependencies). GitNexus (19k stars, Feb 2026) solves this with a code knowledge graph, but its output is locked in LadybugDB with no portable export format.\n\n## Options Evaluated\n\n1. **Complement**: Use GitNexus alongside corvia (two MCP servers). Zero effort but fragmented knowledge, no unified graph.\n2. **Build 80/20 natively**: Extend adapter-git's existing tree-sitter parsing to emit relationship edges for imports, exports, function calls, module dependencies. Not full GitNexus feature set. Just the highest-value structural patterns.\n3. **Adapter integration**: Build adapter-gitnexus to consume GitNexus's KuzuDB/LadybugDB output. Rejected because GitNexus has no export format, schema is undocumented/internal, and it creates a fragile runtime dependency.\n4. **Wait and see**: GitNexus may add export formats later. Rejected because corvia needs a native story regardless.\n\n## Decision\n\n**Option 2: Build the 80/20 natively.** Extend corvia's adapter-git to emit graph edges during ingestion for structural code relationships. Scope limited to what tree-sitter already exposes. No Leiden clustering, no blast radius analysis initially. Just \"what calls what\" and \"what imports what.\"\n\n## Rationale\n\n- Unified knowledge graph is corvia's differentiator. Org memory decisions link to code structure via edges.\n- adapter-git already does tree-sitter parsing. The incremental effort is relationship extraction, not a new parsing pipeline.\n- No external dependency. One tool, one onboarding step.\n- GitNexus integration rejected due to: no export format, LadybugDB schema coupling, runtime dependency, MCP responses designed for LLM consumption not data interchange.\n\n## Scope (80/20)\n\nHigh-value structural edges to emit during ingestion:\n- Import/export relationships between files\n- Function/method call references across files\n- Module dependency graph\n- Class inheritance/implementation relationships\n\nNOT in initial scope: community clustering, blast radius analysis, execution flow tracing, confidence scoring.",
